  "body": "<h3 style=\"text-align: left;margin: 0px;font-size: 18px; line-height:24px; padding-bottom: 0px;padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:15px;margin-top: 10px;padding-left: 0px;padding-right: 0px; font-weight: bold; font-family: Helvetica, Arial, Verdana, Trebuchet MS; color: #222; text-align:center; text-transform:none;\"> <span style=\"display: block; padding-top: 10px; text-align:left; font-weight:normal; font-size: 16px;\">In his 1924 book titled \"The Enjoyment and Use of Color\", author Walter Sargent examines a \"scientifically arranged palette.\"  He states: \"When we have selected colors which are related in hue we have taken one important step toward an orderly arrangement of the palette.  For example, if we use a palette set with only yellow, red, blue, black and white, we have a group of related hues and have thereby limited ourselves to certain tonal effects.  Although this triad is freer from restrictions than any other, still the particular tones of the greens, oranges, and violets which we can produce by mixtures will have a definite kinship with the three colors of the palette.\"\n</span></h3>\n\n\n\n\n\n<table width=\"100%\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\n  <tbody>\n \n    <tr>\n      <td width=\"32%\" align=\"center\" valign=\"bottom\"><a href=\"https://www.bedfordfineartgallery.com/leon_moran_creek.html\"><img style=\"width: 90%; height:auto;\" src=\"https://www.bedfordfineartgallery.com/mailers/img/moran2.jpg\" width=\"198\" height=\"261\" alt=\"Leon Moran (American 1864 – 1941)\n\"></a>\n        <p style=\"font-family:sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight:bold;\">$3,500</p></td>\n        \n           <td width=\"32%\" align=\"center\" valign=\"bottom\"><a href=\"https://www.bedfordfineartgallery.com/max_weyl_sunset.html\"><img style=\"width: 95%; height:auto;\" src=\"https://www.bedfordfineartgallery.com/mailers/img/weyl_cabin.jpg\" width=\"392\" height=\"228\" alt=\"Max Weyl (American 1837 – 1914)\n\"></a>\n        <p 